<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Martre to lose chairman's job at Aerospatiale
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent and ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR HENRI MARTRE, chairman of Aerospatiale, the French state-owned aerospace
group, is to be replaced unexpectedly by Mr Louis Gallois, head of Snecma,
the French state aero-engine company. Mr Gallois' appointment is expected to
be confirmed by the French cabinet tomorrow.
It had been widely thought the government would extend the Aerospatiale
chairman's contract until he retires next February.
The change at the helm of Aerospatiale, a 37.9 per cent partner in the
Airbus airliner consortium, is one of the few surprises in the current round
of top appointments at state-owned French companies.
Last week, Mr Francis Lorentz was replaced as chairman of the loss-making
Bull computer group by Mr Bernard Pache, head of the French coal board and a
former chairman of the Pechiney aluminium group.
Yesterday Generales de France (AGF) and Groupe Nationale des Assurances
(GAN), two of France's largest state-controlled insurance companies, voted
to renominate their chairmen, Mr Michel Albert and Mr Francois Heilbronner.
These nominations are expected to be endorsed tomorrow by the government.
The board of Union des Assurances de Paris, another state-owned insurance
company, meets today, and is expected to renominate its chairman, Mr Jean
Peyrelevade.
Mr Martre has been steering the Aerospatiale through the slump in civil
aviation and the fall in military business caused by the end of the Cold
War.
He has been a leading figure in the fortunes of Airbus and a strong
supporter of European aerospace collaboration.
Mr Gallois had long been regarded as a pretender for Mr Martre's job. A key
adviser to former Socialist prime minister Mr Laurent Fabius, Mr Gallois has
headed Snecma for the past three years where he has sought to carve out a
more individual identity for the French aero-engine group closely tied to
General Electric of the US.
Under Mr Gallois, contacts have improved between the French company and
Rolls-Royce, the UK aero-engine company and one of the main rivals of GE.
</TEXT>
