<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Imro chief quits after criticism of watchdog body over
Maxwell
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, RAYMOND SNODDY and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR GEORGE NISSEN, chairman of Imro, the fund management industry watchdog,
resigned yesterday after widespread criticism of his organisation's role in
the Maxwell affair.
He said Imro was 'open to a share of reproach' but insisted much criticism
of it had been 'misplaced'.
Mr Charles Nunneley, a director of Imro and deputy chairman of Robert
Fleming Holdings, the investment banking group, will act as chairman until a
successor is appointed.
The Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog, is due to
release a report later this week on Imro's supervision of Mr Robert
Maxwell's fund management companies. The report is expected to criticise
Imro for letting Bishopsgate Investment Management (BIM), one of Mr
Maxwell's fund management companies, operate under a looser than normal
regulatory regime.
Imro's report to the SIB on its own supervision of the Maxwell companies
concluded that it could not have barred them from operation but should have
supervised them more closely. It also criticised professional advisers to
the Maxwell pension funds for failing to alert regulators to problems they
uncovered.
Earlier this month, Mr David Corsan, an Imro board member and former partner
at accountants Coopers and Lybrand, announced he would not seek
reappointment. Mr Corsan had been a director of the Maxwell Charitable
Trust, of which BIM was a subsidiary. It also emerged yesterday that two
senior Imro officials closely involved with authorising and supervising Mr
Maxwell's companies have resigned in the past two weeks.
The Financial Services Act requires Imro to decide which fund management
companies are 'fit and proper' to do business and to supervise their
activities. Imro authorised two Maxwell-controlled fund managers, BIM and
London and Bishopsgate International Investment Management.
Mr Frank Field, Labour co-chairman of the cross-party group of MPs
campaigning on behalf of the Maxwell pensioners, applauded Mr Nissen for
resigning and accepting responsibility.
Ms Marjorie Mowlam, Labour's City spokeswoman, also welcomed Mr Nissen's
resignation and called on Mr John Morgan, Imro's chief executive, to do
likewise. Mr Morgan has already said he will retire in September 1993, when
his current contract expires.
Pension pledge, Page 8 Observer, Page 17
