<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Relief supplies land at Sarajevo as UN takes control of
airport
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS, LAURA SILBER and ROBERT MAUTHNER, diplomatic
correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK, BELGRADE, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A FRENCH aircraft carrying relief supplies landed at Sarajevo airport
yesterday, hours after United Nations forces took control of the runway.
Serb irregular forces relinquished their hold on the airport after fierce
international pressure, and were escorted to their barracks south-west of
the besieged Bosnian capital by a 34-man UN force.
After the withdrawal, the UN Security Council, meeting in New York,
unanimously agreed to send 1,000 Canadian troops, on standby in the nearby
former Yugoslav republic of Croatia, to secure the airport.
The Security Council's decision, based on a recommendation from Mr Boutros
Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary-general, could lead in the next few days to
an airlift of humanitarian aid to the city's 300,000 starving inhabitants.
Despite yesterday's developments, General Lewis MacKenzie, UN chief
negotiator in Sarajevo, said full military control of the airport still had
to be established.
However, the French, who had stationed two air force Transall cargo carriers
at the nearby Adriatic port of Split, decided to risk sending in the first
relief flight.
Western diplomats welcomed the news, but said the fighting around the city
was unlikely to stop. Serb forces continued to keep a tight grip on
Sarajevo, renewing their attacks on the city from surrounding hills.
In Washington, the US State Department for the first time refused to rule
out participation of US military personnel in any operation to bring relief
supplies to Sarajevo.
'If the UN votes on a resolution to take all necessary measures to
facilitate provision of humanitarian assistance to the people of
Bosnia-Hercegovina, it would be an action that we would support,' said
department spokeswoman Ms Margaret Tutwiler.
The Canadian battalion, expected in Sarajevo over the next 36 hours, is
equipped with 80 armoured personnel carriers.
The troops will work with French airport technicians to demilitarise the
airport and surrounding areas.
Sixty UN observers and 30 UN police will monitor the withdrawal of Serb
heavy artillery from the airport area and inspect incoming relief supplies
for smuggled weapons.
Robert Mauthner, diplomatic correspondent, in London writes: Foreign Office
officials said any further troops needed to secure Sarajevo airport would
also be supplied by the UN.
There was no shortage of countries ready to contribute troops to a UN force,
but under no circumstances would Britain contribute ground forces to a UN
contingent likely to be involved in fighting.
Protests in Belgrade, Page 2
</TEXT>
