<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Parliament and Politics: Transport minister triesto
safeguard rail deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Roger Freeman, transport minister, offered last night to meet
private-sector financiers personally in an effort to ensure that an
innovative deal to finance new railway rolling stock did not fall through.
NWS Corporate Finance - part of Bank of Scotland - has offered to provide
West Yorkshire Passenger Transport Authority with a 21-year operating lease
covering 14 Class 323 trains for the Leeds-to-Bradford railway line.
The proposed Pounds 30m transaction was described by Mr Freeman last night
as the first 'true' operating lease to have been written in the rail
industry for 70 years.
But the deal has been at risk since the government declined to meet
assurances sought by NWS, formerly IBOS Finance, in order to safeguard its
flow of lease payments. Concerned that government plans to denationalise
British Rail might lead to the privatisation of local transport authorities,
NWS asked the government either to guarantee that there would be no such
change of ownership or to give it an option to demand repayment of the lease
in full in advance of such a change.
The government - which has come under pressure from Yorkshire MPs on both
sides of the Commons - said that no change in transport authorities' status
was planned, but that a guarantee would amount to an unacceptable liability.
Mr Freeman stuck to his position last night, saying the government had no
intention of privatising transport authorities or of changing the method of
their funding. He admitted that the deal had taken 'much longer than we
would have liked' to finalise.
The British Coal and British Rail (Transfer Proposals) Bill received its
third reading last night with a government majority of 62 (278-216).
</TEXT>
