FT  30 JUN 92 / Labour presses for companies 'blacklist'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR FRANK DOBSON, shadow energy secretary, called on the government in the
Commons last night to blacklist companies in the financial services sector
that had any connection with the operations that enabled Robert Maxwell to
plunder pension funds.
He said they should not be given advisory roles in the privatisation of
British Coal or British Rail.
When reminded of Mr Maxwell's associations with the Labour party Mr Dobson
said: 'I do not give a damn which political party Robert Maxwell came from -
he was a villain who stole money from pensioners.'
He added: 'The point I am making is that he did it with the connivance of
innumerable individuals and institutions in the City, because he could not
have done it by himself.'
The government rejected a Labour demand for a provision in the British Coal
and British Rail (Transfer Proposals) Bill to prevent advisory contracts
being awarded to companies under investigation by Department of Trade and
Industry inspectors, or which had been criticised by them.
Mr Tim Eggar, minister for energy, accused Mr Dobson of seeking to stir up
fears and worries about pensions in the coalfield communities and described
his speech as 'an absolute disgrace'.
He dismissed as a 'slur' suggestions that the arrangements enabling British
Coal to stop making payments to pension funds through a 'contributions
holiday' were designed to facilitate a management or employee buyout.
Mr Eggar promised that the pension funds of employees of British Coal and
British Rail would be safeguarded, but when pressed to provide statutory
protection explained that the precise mechanism to be used had still to be
decided.
A clause moved by Mr Dobson was defeated by a government majority of 46
(273-227).
</TEXT>
