<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Government pledge on work schemes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEMBERS OF occupational pension schemes are to be given a new entitlement to
an annual statement saying how much their savings are worth, the government
said yesterday.
It committed itself to the move in a formal response to the report on the
Maxwell affair from the cross-party social security committee of the last
parliament.
The change in the law is, however, unlikely to be immediate. It will
probably be carried out along with the conclusions of the pension law review
committee set up earlier this month to look at pension law and regulation.
The committee, to be chaired by Professor Roy Goode of Oxford University, is
to publish a consultation paper within a few weeks as its first step.
While the government has accepted the main recommendations of the social
security committee, it continues to argue that it does not have any special
responsibility for members of the BIHL pension scheme - the company that was
sold to Robert Maxwell by British Airways in 1986, when BA was still
publicly owned.
Ministers say that BA's articles of association meant that the transport
secretary had to be notified of the decision, but did not have any right of
consent.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, has also moved to tighten
information provision for pension scheme members. Information that must now
be provided, under regulations laid yesterday, includes details about the
pensions ombudsman and the Occupational Pensions Advisory Service and the
ombudsman.
</TEXT>
