<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Sir Leon Brittan commends investment rules
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Leon Brittan, EC financial services commissioner, yesterday promised
that the agreement reached on the Investment Services Directive (ISD) would
be 'good news for the City of London' as the capital requirements and
trading rules were not designed to damage any market.
He was speaking after EC finance ministers reached an agreement on the ISD
last night.
His statement will be greeted with relief by the financial services houses
in London, many of which were concerned that the ISD might force them to
publish information on security prices and volumes, and so put them at a
disadvantage.
The main issue that concerned the City was transparency, which would require
securities houses to publish price and volume information on a screen-based
system.
Some of the EC member countries were pushing for immediate publication of
such information. Many of the UK-based securities houses were anxious,
however, that the immediate release of such information in the market might
work against their interests.
Market makers in securities argued that if they were forced to buy a large
block of shares from an institution and the information became available to
the market immediately, their competitors would be able to mark the price
down, possibly forcing them to sell the shares at a loss.
The solution agreed yesterday was broadly what had been expected by several
large financial service houses in the UK.
The question of freedom of access - banks will automatically be allowed to
join as members of European stock exchanges - is seen as significant for the
German commercial banks. . Until now they have not been able to enjoy full
membership.
A senior adviser at a US securities house said: 'Progress on the ISD is
important as it means that further liberalisation of the European financial
markets will be possible.'
</TEXT>
