<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Consumers fail to lead recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE is still no sign of a consumer-led recovery, according to a survey of
more than 1,000 adults published today by Mintel, the market research
organisation.
Mintel concluded that a 'consumer-driven' recovery, instigated by the
government and financial institutions, would be needed.
It added that the UK population had suffered 'its greatest shock since the
Second World War' and was 'understandably cautious'.
According to the survey, 59 per cent of consumers felt that borrowing money
for anything other than buying a house should be avoided.
A strong majority - 65 per cent - also said they were not prepared to use
credit cards to buy from sales. On the strength of those figures, Mintel
predicted that the next quarter will show a net repayment of consumer
credit.
Meanwhile, two thirds said they intended to put money aside for a rainy day,
and more than half of the sample said they would want to put money into
long-term tax-efficient investments.
Mr Paul Hersey, senior researcher, pointed out that youngsters -
particularly those in the 15-19 age group - had grown significantly more
conservative in their financial outlook over the past few years. He said:
'Three years ago, 15-to-19-year-olds were far more likely to look at
borrowing than they are now. Now it's a question of save now and borrow
later for them.'
However, there were some causes for hope, as a slim majority (48 per cent)
agreed with the statement that 'I feel quite confident in the outlook for
the UK economy', while 46 per cent disagreed. Only 37 per cent are worried
about their long-term financial security.
He said: 'People are not going to rush out and spend money. They still
remember the rapid hike in interest rates in 1989, and many are still
recovering from the extra costs they incurred then, so they are building a
cushion for themselves.'
The report concluded by saying that long-term optimism might mean that
recovery, when it happens, could be 'very fast'.
The Election &amp; Recovery? Mintel International, 18-19 Long Lane, London EC1A
9HE. Warning, Overset column Pounds 325.
</TEXT>
