<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Small businesses attack Tec policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SMALL businesses are poorly represented on the boards of Training and
Enterprise Councils, according to a survey by the Federation of Small
Businesses.
Only nine of the Tecs that responded to the survey had a good spread of
board members from the small-business sector while 37 had inadequate
representation, the survey showed. Sixty-three of the 82 English and Welsh
Tecs took part in the survey.
With 97 per cent of all businesses employing fewer than 20 people, a strong
case could be made for most of Tec board seats intended for employers to go
to small businesses, the federation said.
Ms Ro Pengelly, head of the federation's employment affairs, said: 'Adequate
representation seems to be the exception rather than the rule. The survey
revealed an unsympathetic attitude by many Tecs towards the small business
sector.'
Even when Tecs had small-business representatives, they often came from
local enterprise agencies or the economic development units of local
councils. They were business advisers rather than owner-managers of small
businesses.
The federation said Tecs often appeared confused about what a small business
was. Most defined a small business as one employing fewer than 100 people,
although the federation regarded that as a medium-sized business.
Small businesses should be represented at the highest level on the Tecs and
not just in advisory groups or policy forums, the federation said.
The government guidelines say that local-business leaders on Tec boards
should be selected for their individual qualities and not just as
representatives of existing organisations. They also require boards to
reflect an area's range of industry and commerce.
Letters, Page 17
</TEXT>
