<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Stolen computers head east
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PERSONAL computers, fax machines and photocopiers are being stolen on an
organised basis in northern England to feed shortages in eastern Europe,
police believe.
Secondhand markets have collapsed in Britain because of price cutting by
manufacturers.
Greater Manchester police say eastern Europe appears to be the only place
where the returns justify the risks of large-scale crime.
Organised theft of office equipment was identified last year when Bradford
police used a computer to search for patterns of crime. They found that
Pounds 1.57m of office equipment had been stolen in the city in the previous
12 months. Typical insurance claims after a raid are more than Pounds
10,000.
Thieves go to elaborate lengths, often posing as service or removal
specialists to raid offices.
Greater Manchester police have approached Customs and Excise to see if
manifests and bills of lading can be checked for stolen computers and other
electronic office equipment being shipped to eastern Europe.
Detective Chief Inspector Ian Martin said he was applying for Pounds 1,000
from the Home Office's Safer Cities crime prevention campaign to buy a
branding iron with an interchangeable head. Police will then be able to
visit offices and brand a company's postcode into the plastic fascia of
expensive equipment.
'This will make it easier to check goods being offered at car boot sales,
auctions or exported,' he said.
</TEXT>
