<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / 'Green' audit figures up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE PROPORTION of companies mentioning environmental issues in their annual
reports has doubled to almost a fifth in the past year, but few provide much
useful information, according to Company Reporting, the Edinburgh-based
monthly monitoring service.
About 18 per cent of companies that produced accounts in the last 12 months
address 'green' concerns, but half of those provide vague and general
statements that do not describe any action being taken, it says.
For example, Kingfisher, the retailing group, which has projected an image
of corporate responsibility, simply states its commitment to improving
environmental performance and agreeing a policy with its board, without
giving any details.
Among the more interesting disclosures, National Westminster Bank says it
takes environmental considerations into account when assessing loans. Austin
Reed, the clothing manufacturer and retailer, encourages suppliers to meet
environmental standards it sets.
Separately, Company Reporting says that less than 3 per cent of companies
provide any forecast information in their annual reports, in spite of a call
for details of future developments in the European Community's 7th directive
on company accounts.
From a sample of 590 companies, 1.7 per cent highlight forecast information,
a further 1.2 per cent provide some forward-looking details, and 0.3 per
cent state that it is too difficult to make any forecasts.
</TEXT>
