<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Accords in rail disputes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
CONRAIL and Amtrak, two of the biggest US rail operators, said they had
reached tentative labour accords with their track workers, a significant
step toward resolving the various disputes affecting the US industry, writes
Alan Friedman in New York.
Conrail, one of the largest freight operators, said it reached an agreement
with representatives of the Brotherhood of Maintenance of Way Employees
(BMWE), which has 3,100 Conrail workers. Amtrak, the passenger service, said
it struck a deal with BMWE officials representing 2,100 of its workers. Both
settlements were reached last weekend and announced last night.
The accords came after Congress acted last Thursday night to end a 48-hour
strike against one big operator by approving legislation that ordered rail
employees back to work. Congress also set guidelines for binding arbitration
should parties find it impossible to settle their disputes.
Amtrak said the accord meant it had resolved outstanding labour problems
with 17 of its 19 unions.
</TEXT>
