<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / EC ministers open up rules on Community share deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN and SARA WEBB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LUXEMBOURG, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTMENT FIRMS will have a 'single passport' to deal in shares around the
European Community under an agreement reached among EC finance ministers
last night.
The new directive, reached after two years' wrangling, gives stockbrokers in
one country the right to deal in shares of any other EC country without
having to set up a local office or buy a local stockbroker.
The Investment Services Directive (ISD) is seen as the last important plank
in measures to open Europe's financial markets. The agreement still has to
pass through the European Parliament but Mr Norman Lamont, the UK
chancellor, said he was 'well satisfied'.
Many City institutions were anxious to avoid any directive which might
damage London's role as a financial centre. They were particularly concerned
about the question of transparency, fearing they would suffer if they had to
disclose full details of transactions - including sensitive information on
prices and volumes - immediately. Much of the debate on the transparency
issue concerned the question of allowing a time delay before disclosing
price and volume.
Under a complex formula setting out how soon off-market share transactions
should be made public, the final agreement would provide for:
A weighted average of prices and volumes in transactions over a six-hour
period to be published two hours later.
The highest and lowest prices, calculated over a rolling two-hour period,
would be published every 20 minutes, with one hour's delay.
As a safeguard - insisted on by the UK - these disclosure rules could be
suspended for very large trades or transactions in illiquid stocks.
Sir Leon Brittan, the EC commissioner responsible for financial services,
said yesterday's accord gave legitimate investors 'a reasonable amount of
information, while enabling the markets to function with liquidity'.
Ministers also agreed on the final disputed aspect of the capital adequacy
directive. Under this, securities dealers would have to have a minimum
amount of capital, depending on the size of the investment firm and the
nature of the risk of its transactions to get their 'passport'.
The formula is designed to bridge the conflicting interests between Britain
and some other countries, particularly France.
The UK was concerned for its 'quote-driven' system, which depends on
market-makers' readiness to hold large blocks of shares while keeping the
exact size of the blocks private. In many countries, stockbrokers and banks
start hunting for shares only after receiving a client's order.
Ministers also agreed on a phased timetable for six countries to allow banks
direct access to their stock markets.
Sir Leon Brittan commends investment rules, Page 6
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
