FT  30 JUN 92 / Letter: Federation not a front-runner
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From JOOP VAN ANTWERPEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Reading your article 'Germans urge rethink of European Union' (June
25), I was struck by the statement that Germany's industrial federation
(BDI) has traditionally been one of the most enthusiastic supporters of EMU
among Europe's employers' organisations. In my view, BDI never was a
front-runner in EC matters, nor were German trade unions. It took several
years before they mentally endorsed the success of the EMS.
When BDI quotes that 'the speed of integration has been too fast', I wonder
what kind of integration they are after. Is dismantling 280 trade fences
installed on nationalistic subsidiarity level, for instance, already a
bridge too far? How many bureaucrats were maintaining these obstacles?
Joop van Antwerpen,
9 Wilhelminalaan,
3701 BC ZEIST - Netherlands
