FT  30 JUN 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
We are promised that BBC2's Black And White In Colour will tell us about
'Television, memory and race, 1968 to 1992'.
Will it celebrate the success story of black people on British television?
Will it point out that in a population more than 95 per cent white, the
proportion of prominent black sportsmen, comedians, and pop groups on
television is well above the proportion of black people in the population?
Will it applaud a system which, despite some racist feeling of the sort you
find the world over, in populations of all colours, brings us journalists
such as Zeinab Badawi, Stuart Hall, Trevor McDonald, Trevor Phillips and
Moira Stuart?
Or will it be the usual old resentful defeatism that we get from
television's race industry depressives? We shall see (8.10).
Tonight also brings Rear Window (9.00 C4) which visits Rajasthan for its
account of Indian miniatures; Madhur Jaffrey starring in the drama about two
women who start a catering business, Firm Friends (9.00 ITV); and a repeat
of a 1964 documentary about Afro-Caribbeans living in Birmingham, The Colony
(11.15 BBC2).
