<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Buildings shake-up urged in education
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor and PAUL CHEESERIGHT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MUCH of the increase in UK student numbers planned for the 1990s could be
accommodated in existing buildings if better use was made of them, according
to a report by the university and polytechnic funding councils.
More than half the 300,000 increase in students could be accommodated if
higher education institutions improved space management and remodelled
existing buildings, the report says.
An additional 117,000 places would be needed by the end of the century,
however, plus extra spending on equipment, libraries, central support and
social facilities. The report, published yesterday, recommends the creation
of a higher-education finance corporation to facilitate borrowing from
financial institutions.
Proposals for making better use of existing space in universities and
polytechnics include:
Increasing the size of teaching groups.
Opening teaching space for longer hours and on Saturdays.
Addition of a fourth term or switching to the three-semester system (where
the present three terms are lengthened, with students divided into groups
that attend only two of the three terms).
Universities and polytechnics would find it easier to raise finance on the
capital markets if government-imposed restraints on using their assets to
raise funds were lifted. Lincolnshire County Council is likely to provide
Pounds 10m as initial financing for a university in Lincoln, Paul
Cheeseright writes.
Nottingham Polytechnic has been chosen to supervise the opening of and
manage a university college in the city by 1996, and create an independent
university early next century. A meeting of the council's education
committee recommended the funding.
</TEXT>
