<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Annual statement pledge for pension schemes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MEMBERS OF occupational pension schemes are to be given a new entitlement to
an annual statement saying how much their savings are worth, the government
said yesterday.
The government committed itself to the move in its formal response to the
report on the Maxwell affair from the cross-party social security committee
of the last parliament.
The change in the law is, however, unlikely to be immediate. It will
probably be carried out along with the conclusions of the committee given
the task of reviewing pension law and regulation earlier this month. The
committee, to be chaired by Professor Roy Goode of Oxford University, is to
publish a consultation paper within a few weeks.
While the government has accepted the main recommendations of the social
security committee, it continues to argue that it does not have any special
responsibility for members of the BIHL pension scheme - the company that was
sold to Robert Maxwell by British Airways in 1986, when BA was still
publicly owned.
Ministers say BA's articles of association meant that the transport
secretary had to be notified of the decision, but did not have any right of
consent.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, has also moved to tighten
information provision for pension scheme members. Information that must now
be provided, under regulations laid yesterday, includes details about the
Occupational Pensions Advisory Service and the ombudsman.
The other members of the pension law review committee were announced
yesterday. They are: Mr Tony Atkinson, professor at the London School of
Economics, Mr David Berridge, Scottish Equitable Life Assurance chief
executive, Mr Harvie Brown, actuary at William Mercer Fraser Ltd, Mr Bryan
Hines, former ICI general manager of insurance and investments, Mr Stuart
James, a partner at Rowe and Maw, Mr Terence Libby, Morrisflex chief
executive, Mr Alastair Ross-Goobey, James Capel chief investment strategist,
Ms Patricia Triggs, a partner of KPMG Peat Marwick McLintock and Ms Sue
Ward, a freelance journalist and researcher on pensions issues.
</TEXT>
