<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Councils close to a deal with white-collar workers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOCAL authorities moved close to a pay deal with 750,000 white-collar
workers yesterday as union leaders advised that rises of between 4 per cent
and 4.4 per cent were the best that could be achieved through negotiation.
The proposed deal will set the tone for talks covering 1m blue-collar
workers. It would raise the pay bill by 4.1 per cent, although an earlier
settlement covering residential social workers will add another 0.2 per
cent.
The offer is weighted to favour the lowest-paid, who would gain rises of 4.4
per cent. Those at the top end of the scale would receive 4 per cent.
Although it would be the lowest settlement for white-collar workers in
recent years - and below the inflation rate of 4.3 per cent - it comes at a
time when workers generally are reluctant to take industrial action.
Negotiators for Nalgo, the largest union among council white-collar workers,
traditionally recommend strike action, but only once in the past seven years
has their advice been heeded.
Union leaders want to concentrate on winning a 'yes' vote for a merger with
the Nupe and Cohse unions. The amalgamation ballot is scheduled to take
place at the end of this year.
Nalgo negotiators believe industrial action would achieve little. Mr Dennis
Reed, Nalgo's local government officer, said the offer did not meet the
union's objectives but members were presented with the stark choice of an
unsatisfactory offer or strike action.
The proposed deal will be be presented to the union's local government group
on July 22.
</TEXT>
