FT  30 JUN 92 / BCCI creditors drop compensation appeal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK creditors' committee of Bank of Credit and Commerce International has
dropped its appeal against a High Court ruling that sanctioned a Dollars
1.7bn compensation package negotiated between Touche Ross, the liquidators,
and the bank's Abu Dhabi majority shareholders.
The creditors abandoned their appeal when they were told that they might be
personally liable for costs in the action rather than being able to recover
appeal costs from BCCI assets.
A similar ruling to the UK approval in Grand Cayman left the liquidators
seeking one final approval in Luxembourg today to get all the court
approvals necessary for the agreement to proceed.
Agreement to the package by the Luxembourg court would leave Touche Ross
needing acceptances from creditors representing 51 per cent of the
identified liabilities before it begins making staged payments to creditors
early next year.
According to Touche Ross, the deal should return to the creditors between 30
and 40 per cent of their original investment.
