<PROFILE>_AN-CF3ATAATFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920630
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  30 JUN 92 / Job survey lifts hope for union chiefs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   UNION density figures
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
the proportion of union members to the total workforce - have made gloomy
reading for union leaders for more than a decade.
The latest Department of Employment Labour Force Survey (LFS) showed density
slipping to 37.5 per cent of the workforce last year.
However, the survey, plus unpublished data from the Engineering Employers
Federation, provides a few fragments of hope for union bosses as well as
some statistical curiosities.
The density figure for part-time workers - a growing but
difficult-to-unionise part of the workforce - grew slightly from 21 per cent
to 22 per cent last year, according to the Labour Research Department
analysis of the LFS.
That helps to explain why union density for women, who make up the bulk of
part-time workers, stayed at 32 per cent last year while male density
dropped from 43 per cent to 42 per cent.
Manual workers are still more likely to be in unions than white-collar
workers - 41 per cent compared with 35 per cent - but union density is
highest of all in 'professional occupations', possibly explained by high
unionisation among teachers. The lowest level of unionisation is among
'sales occupations', at 15 per cent.
Only nine of 49 job categories saw union density rise last year - one was
property dealers, no doubt responding to the threat of redundancy in the
troubled estates market. The biggest fall in union density was in the water
industry - 82 per cent to 74 per cent - probably as a result of
privatisation in England and Wales in 1988.
Next came telecommunications (80 per cent to 73 per cent) as a result of job
transfers from unionised British Telecom to non-union Mercury.
In the 1980s, union density fell sharply everywhere except in the public
sector. Even manufacturing, the heartland of unionisation in the private
sector, saw a big fall in density and not just in absolute numbers. The
manufacturing workforce has fallen from 7m in 1979 to about 4.5m.
According to LFS figures, union density was about 58 per cent in
manufacturing in 1984 and had fallen to 47 per cent by 1989. Department of
Employment statisticians believe it is now just above 40 per cent. That is
not because there has been widespread derecognition where unions are already
established, but because the few new manufacturing jobs, often in the
electronics sector, are generally not unionised.
Within manufacturing companies there has been a reduction in hourly paid
manual employment and an increase in white-collar and professional jobs,
which are less likely to be unionised.
A detailed survey of about a quarter of the 5,000-plus companies affiliated
to the Engineering Employers Federation shows that the engineering core of
manufacturing remains solidly unionised. Of 1,300 companies surveyed, 62 per
cent recognise unions for collective bargaining, representing 79 per cent of
the total number of workers employed by the sample.
A total of 86 per cent of hourly paid workers in those companies are covered
by collective bargaining and a surprisingly high 69 per cent of staff. There
is interest in simplifying collective bargaining and harmonising conditions
between white and blue-collar workers, but only 7 per cent of the companies
negotiate for both groups together.
The likelihood of collective bargaining rises with the size of
establishment. All those with more than 1,000 workers have collective
bargaining.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
