   SANTIAGO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Patricio Aylwin's government has won a solid vote of confidence in
the first municipal elections to be held in Chile since 1973, with the
ruling coalition of Christian Democrats and left-wing parties polling 53.3
per cent of the votes in Sunday's contest.
The president, who is now more than half way through his four-year term,
said the vote gave him a clear mandate to reform the anti-democratic
constitution inherited from the military.
Having cleared the municipal hurdle, the government appears set to win
presidential and parliamentary elections, to be held in December 1993.
Chile's right-wing opposition alliance fell short of expectation, polling
29.8 per cent of the votes - four points below their showing in the 1989
general election.
