<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / IBM forms alliance to develop PC multimedia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNATIONAL Business Machines (IBM), the world's largest computer
manufacturer, has formed an alliance with Videologic, a small UK electronics
company, to accelerate the growth of one of the most promising new computing
technologies.
The technology, 'multimedia', combines computer text and graphics with
moving video images and stereophonic sound on a personal computer screen. It
promises to bring greater verisimilitude and ease of use to computing
applications ranging from business analysis to games.
Industry experts believe the development of multimedia applications could
rejuvenate the personal-computer sector, which is flagging because of market
saturation and a decline in product innovation.
Multimedia has been slow to take off, chiefly because of the difficulty of
developing applications that use its full potential. Creating a multimedia
computer program has so far been the province of experts using expensive
equipment.
The goal of IBM and Videologic, a wholly owned subsidiary of Avesco, a video
equipment supplier, is to create products that will make the writing of
multimedia programs cheaper and simpler.
Videologic is a world leader in interactive video technology. In 1989 it
pioneered a way of controlling moving video images on a computer screen
which significantly cut the cost of image processing. Avesco made a profit
on sales of about Pounds 20m last year.
No equity or board-level participation is involved in the joint venture, but
there will be close co-ordination between the two companies as they develop
semiconductor chips, electronic circuitry and software that can be slotted
into personal computers to enable them to be used as workstations for the
development of multimedia applications.
</TEXT>
