FT  29 JUN 92 / Kinnock predicted defeat in election
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR NEIL KINNOCK yesterday said that four days before the general election he
had realised that his party's internal strife during the early 1980s would
lead to its defeat.
Speaking two weeks before he stands down as Labour leader, Mr Kinnock said
that on the Sunday before the election his personal instincts and polling
data had signalled that Labour had not done enough to win back the trust of
the electorate.
Between 4 and 5 per cent of the electorate did not have sufficient trust in
the party because of the 'months of turmoil' under the last Labour
government in 1979 and the 'years of conflict' in the early 1980s.
Speaking to Mr David Frost on TV-am, Mr Kinnock said that to win back that
trust Labour would have to further reduce the power of the trades unions in
decision-making.
In spite of last week's decision by Labour's National Executive Committee to
delay any change for at least a year, Mr Kinnock said he was convinced that
the party would move to a one member, one vote system for the selection of
parliamentary candidates.
