<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Auditors' duties to regulators defined
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AUDITORS to investment businesses must examine any breaches of rules that
might lead to de-authorisation of the businesses, new notes from the
Auditing Practices Board said yesterday.
The notes cover the reporting requirements of regulatory bodies for
investment businesses, including the Securities and Investments Board.
While auditors are not responsible for checking compliance with rules - such
as the requirement to give 'best advice' to clients - they must take into
consideration any claims or fines that might lead to withdrawal of
authorisation to conduct business, they say.
Auditors' main responsibility is to provide assurance to regulators on the
financial information provided by businesses, the accounting records and
control systems, and the stewardship of client assets.
The notes lay out a standard form for reports to regulators that provides
clear, unambiguous wording.
The APB has deferred potentially controversial amendments to existing
guidelines on 'ad hoc' or whistle-blowing reports to government regulatory
bodies.
Those allow auditors to report matters to the regulator without breaching
client confidentiality.
APB Practice Note 1. PO Box 620, Central Milton Keynes. MK9 2JX. Pounds
6.50.
</TEXT>
