<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Lloyd's moves on efficiency
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FIRST STEPS towards possible broad changes in the management of Lloyd's of
London will be taken this week as the troubled insurance market braces
itself for the results of two extensive inquiries.
The opening on Wednesday of an office intended to raise the efficiency of
claims processing may be followed by a rationalisation at the Lloyd's
corporation, which regulates and provides services to the 278 underwriting
syndicates.
The management of the market will figure prominently in one of two
long-awaited reports, scheduled to be considered by the Lloyd's Council, the
governing body, also on Wednesday. The report, drawn up by a committee
headed by Sir Jeremy Morse, chairman of Lloyds Bank, will also focus on the
regulation of the market.
A second report, prepared by a separate committee led by Sir David Walker,
chairman of the Securities and Investments Board, the City watchdog, will
also be put before the council. Sir David has investigated allegations that
working Names - individuals who provide the market's capital - have
benefited at the expense of outside Names.
Last week Lloyd's reported its worst-ever losses of Pounds 2.06bn for 1989,
in time with its three-year accounting system.
The market, which faces legal action from financially embarrassesd Names, is
under pressure to adopt wide reforms.
The new claims office will have more freedom to operate along commercial
lines than its predecessor, the marine claims office. It will assume the
functions of the aviation and non-marine claims offices, owned by
associations of Lloyd's underwriters.
The office will have wide powers to set staff levels and pay and will be
able to buy in services rather than rely on the corporation's resources. In
the past, underwriters and the agencies which manage them have criticised
what they have seen as excessive bureaucracy in the market.
</TEXT>
