<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Bank succeeds with republican coup
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CENTRAL bankers from the republics of the former Soviet Union will enrol in
London today on a special two-week Bank of England seminar.
The Bank's Centre for Central Banking Studies - sometimes known as the Old
Lady's Academy - is expecting to play host to the heads of 10 of the 15
central banks set up since the collapse of the Soviet Union, including those
of Russia, the Ukraine and Kazakhstan. Senior representatives of three other
central banks from former Soviet republics will attend the course.
It will be the first time the heads or their representatives of the
republics' central banks will have met abroad since the break-up of the
USSR.
Subjects to be covered include monetary policy, the creation of separate
currencies, currency convertibility and the development of financial
markets. Relations between fiscal policy and monetary policy, banking
supervision and press relations are also on the agenda.
The Bank believes it has achieved something of a coup in attracting nearly
all the former Soviet republics' top central bankers to a single event.
Providing the former eastern bloc with central banking knowhow, and the
influence that goes with it, has become a highly competitive field, with
foreign central banks such as the German Bundesbank and Austrian National
Bank also playing an active role.
The Bank has provided training for staff of other central banks since the
1950s. In September it set up the Centre for Central Banking Studies to meet
increased demand for such training after the demise of communism in eastern
Europe and the former Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
