<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Paisley may meet Irish ministers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK and Irish governments are preparing for a potentially difficult
meeting tomorrow on the future of Northern Ireland that may bring the Rev
Ian Paisley, the hardline Democratic Unionist party leader, face to face
with Irish ministers, Ralph Atkins writes.
The London meeting, agreed only after two weeks of wrangling between the
governments over dates, will officially be to 'give preliminary
consideration to the issues likely to arise' in the third 'strand' of the
nine-week-old all-party talks process. This strand is concerned with
relations between the two countries.
Unionists regard the meeting as a crucial time for British ministers to
press for removal of the Irish constitutional claim on Northern Ireland. The
Irish government is putting more emphasis on persuading Sir Patrick Mayhew,
Northern Ireland secretary, to formally start 'strand two' of the talks - on
relations between Northern Ireland and the Irish republic.
Tomorrow's agenda was confirmed in talks between Mr John Major and Mr Albert
Reynolds, the Irish premier, at the European Community summit in Lisbon. The
meeting is part of the complex deal struck by Sir Patrick this month to keep
the talks going even though agreement has not been reached in 'strand one' -
on models of government for the province.
The meeting is meant to be between the two governments, but Northern
Ireland's main political parties will send observers. The DUP is expected to
decide today to send Mr Paisley - more to ensure that the UK government is
sufficiently forthright than to put pressure on the Irish.
</TEXT>
