<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Thatcher sets stage for bitter confrontations: The former
PM's latest European onslaught
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IF MR JOHN MAJOR had harboured hopes that Mrs Margaret Thatcher's elevation
to the House of Lords would signal a period of silence, they were
comprehensively shattered by her onslaught yesterday against virtually all
things European.
The startling passion with which Mrs Thatcher denounced Maastricht - on her
entry into the Lords tomorrow she will become Baroness Thatcher of Kesteven
 -set the stage for a series of bitter confrontations over the next few
months.
As worrying for the government was that, as standardbearer of the Tory
rebellion over Maastricht, she signalled she felt she would feel free to
attack her successor over a broad range of issues.
Cabinet ministers were horrified by the content and tone of her remarks. The
former prime minister should be reminded, they suggested, that she had
campaigned in the general election on a manifesto that hailed Maastricht as
a triumph. But after a period of erratic loyalty during the approach to the
election, her friends say Mrs Thatcher sees no reason to keep quiet now
about issues of 'principle'.
Her warning that Britain could not expect economic recovery until it
decoupled its borrowing costs from high German rates echoed a series of
attacks by rebel Tories on sterling's participation in the exchange rate
mechanism.
Mrs Thatcher - who was persuaded by Mr Major two months before her
resignation to take sterling into the system - was careful not to advocate
withdrawal from the ERM. But she backed calls for immediate cuts in interest
rates to get the economy moving, if necessary at the expense of devaluing
sterling against the D-Mark.
A policy of high interest rates that was right for Germany, she said, was
causing growing unemployment in Britain. 'You will not get economic recovery
in this country while this interest rate stays as high.'
There was also a warning shot over public spending, as Mrs Thatcher reminded
Mr Major that while she was prime minister the government presided over
large surpluses. Her successor had to be 'very careful', as sound finance
was the basis for commanding respect abroad.
But it was on the future of Europe that Mrs Thatcher was at her most
scathing. For her, Maastricht is irredeemable. Even with its opt-outs for
Britain on monetary union and the social charter, it would strike at the
heart of parliamentary democracy.
It would create a European union that had its own citizenship, currency and
foreign and defence policies. 'It is the structure of a federal state,' she
said.
Mrs Thatcher dismissed as 'gobbledegook' the principle of 'subsidiarity'
which Mr Major has put at the centre of his approach to European
integration. She attacked his decision to back the extension of Mr Jacques
Delors' term as European Commission president. She applauded the Danish vote
against Maastricht. She argued that it had 'saved parliamentary democracy in
this country'.
If Mr Major pressed ahead with ratification of the treaties, she warned, she
would vote against him. Even if Mr Major's leadership was threatened by such
a rebellion, although Mrs Thatcher did not believe there would be such a
challenge. She told Tory opponents of Maastricht to 'vote on what you
believe'.
Mr Major's colleagues believe that in the end such attacks will be
counter-productive. The Conservative party in the country had worshipped Mrs
Thatcher, but it would not back disloyalty. Though guaranteed publicity this
week, her attacks would be a 'devaluing currency'.
Ministers also believe that if the legislation to ratify Maastricht is
framed as a confidence issue, then only a small hard core of Tory
'irreconcilables' will vote against it.
Until then, they acknow-ledge that Mrs Thatcher is likely to provide a focus
for a damaging and distracting rebellion.
</TEXT>
