<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Committee boost to top pay seen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHIEF EXECUTIVES whose pay is determined by remuneration committees are paid
nearly 20 per cent more than colleagues at companies without such
arrangements, according to a report which will fuel the debate over the role
of non-executive directors.
The study, led by Professor Brian Main of Edinburgh University's economics
department and published in today's Personnel Management magazine, is based
on a survey of 220 of the UK's largest companies, 67 of which were
identified as having a remuneration sub-committee of the board.
The establishment of remuneration committees was one of the main
recommendations of the recent Cadbury committee report on corporate
governance.
The research by Prof Main and Mr James Johnston, a research fellow
colleague, found that the average chief executive salary was Pounds 313,500
in companies with remuneration committees and Pounds 245,700 in those
without them. With the value of executive stock options added, the figures
were Pounds 1.15m against Pounds 930,000 in favour of companies with
remuneration committees.
In an additional article in the magazine, Prof Main and Mr Johnston say the
challenge to committees is 'not so much to hold pay levels down as to
structure pay in a way that provided the maximum incentive by linking pay to
performance'.
The study, however, found no significant difference in the proportion of
options, one gauge of performance pay, in the executives' remuneration
package. It also found that a chief executive whose compensation committee
includes non-executive directors who are particularly well paid by their own
company is likely to be paid more in turn.
The authors conclude that 'merely setting up a remuneration committee is no
answer to the problem of controlling top executive pay'. It adds: 'At the
moment in Britain, these committees seem to do little more than legitimise
generous pay awards. In general, these findings suggest that innovations in
corporate governance do not promise an immediate or radical transformation
in the way top executives are paid.'
The report says attention should be paid to the way non-executive
directorships are filled. 'There is clear scope for greater shareholder
activism, both in demanding greater disclosure of the nature of the
deliberations of the committees and by securing non-executive directorships
for shareholder representatives.'
The survey found that remuneration committees were more common among larger
companies - 40 per cent among those with an annual turnover of more than
Pounds 1.5bn and 17 per cent among those with less than Pounds 500m. Less
than half of the 67 remuneration committees were totally free of executive
membership. There were many cases where executives sat on the committee that
determined their own pay.
</TEXT>
