<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Recession overturns southern and regional divide
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE lingering recession has overturned the caricatured relationship between
Britain's southern economic core and its regional periphery. The southern
regions have fared badly while Scotland and Northern Ireland have escaped
relatively unscathed.
Yet the slow spread of the recession from services into manufacturing means
the west Midlands has suffered the sharpest fall in output over the last
eight quarters, according to Business Strategies, the regional consultancy.
The service and consumer-oriented recession was largely a punishment for the
excessive growth rates enjoyed by London and the south-east in the latter
half of the 1980s. Rapid southern growth and the lingering side effects of
the last, northern-biased recession, opened wide north-south gaps in
unemployment rates, house prices and incomes per head.
But Britain's economic boom proved unsustainable and the combination of
heavy debts, high real interest rates and falling house prices affected the
spending power of southern consumers worse than less indebted consumers
elsewhere.
Across a wide range of economic indicators - unemployment, house prices,
bankruptcies - the southern regions have fared worst. The south-east may
still have a lower unemployment rate than the average, but the difference
has closed to 0.5 percentage points from 1.5 percentage points when the
recession started, and 2.8 percentage points in 1987.
The south's hangover is likely to impede economic recovery this year.
National Westminster Bank expects a sluggish recovery to be led by Wales,
the north of England and Scotland. The wealth and economic power of southern
Britain means that those regions are expected to experience above-average
growth rates when the economy shakes off its lethargy.
NatWest expects the fastest growth rates in the next five years to be
experienced by the four regions bordering the south-east.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
ANATOMY OF THE RECESSION
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
NORTH-WEST
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Slowdown rather than shutdown, thanks to the diversity and strength of
Greater Manchester. Bus scars from the last recession remain,
particularly in Merseyside.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
'Our central concern is the contraction of the defence and aviation
industries. We have a skilled workforce increasingly without work,
markets and prospects.'
Basil Jeuda, managing director of Inward, the north-west investment
agency.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
SCOTLAND
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Mild recession caused much less pain than in the over-borrowed south.
North Sea oil industry has flourished and manufacturing exports have
held up well.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
'If the recovery does come to the south east it will be a challenge
for Scotland to match it. People down there still have more money to
spend.'
Ron Garrick, chief executive of the Weir Group, the engineering company
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
WEST MIDLANDS
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Deep recession interrupted recovery from the early 1980s shakeout in
engineering and halted the more recent service sector expansion.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
'Business across a wide spread of products and services is, at best,
flat and the economy is likely to remain that way for the rest of the
year.'
Gareth Davies, chairman of Glynwed International, the engineering group.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
SOUTH-EAST
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
Bore the brunt of the service-sector recession, but the region's wealth
and proximity to Europe make it a good growth bet when the recovery
finally materialises.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
'We would expect the recent, very gradual uplift in the retail sector
to continue. How the south responds will largely determine the strength
of Britain's economic recovery.'
Nigel Whittaker, director of Kingfisher, the retail conglomerate.
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
</TEXT>
