<DATE>920629
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Mitterrand in Sarajevo: EC pins blame on Serbia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK BLUM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LISBON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Community agreed at the weekend to step up pressure on Serbia,
called for the dispatch of observers to Kosovo and neighbouring countries,
and moved a step closer towards granting full recognition to Macedonia.
EC leaders, fearing that the war in Yugoslavia will spread to other Balkan
countries, said they would not recognise the new federal republic of Serbia
and Montenegro as the successor state of the former Yugoslavia until other
international institutions had done so, and demanded the suspension of the
delegation of the former Yugoslavia at the Conference on Security and
Co-operation in Europe and other international organisations.
At the same time they left open the possibility of force being used by the
UN to re-open Sarajevo airport and allow humanitarian supplies to be flown
in.
In Washington yesterday, President George Bush, who again conferred with EC
leaders by telephone, said the US 'will do its part' to see aid was
delivered. He said Washington intended to handle the situation in accord
with the UN and he declined to comment further on possible US actions.
In a further development last night, Tanjug, the Belgrade-based news agency,
said that the Bosnian-Serb leadership had handed over control of Sarajevo
airport to UN peace-keeping forces. This could pave the way for humanitarian
aid, although the UN commander in Sarajevo denied later that his troops had
full responsibility for the airport yet.
The EC declaration firmly pinned blame on Serbia for the continuing violence
in Bosnia. 'Although all parties have contributed in their own way (to the
fighting), by far the greatest share of responsibility falls on the Serbian
leadership and the Yugoslav army controlled by it,' it said.
Some EC states, led by France and Italy and followed by Germany, had wanted
the Community to adopt more specific measures to ensure emergency supplies
could be flown in. Italy argued that force should be used to reopen the
airport, while France and Germany pressed for tough action, though they fell
short of calling for direct military intervention.
Others remained cautious. The British prime minister, Mr John Major, argued
that a ceasefire would have to be in force before an airlift could be
carried out.
In the end leaders agreed the EC would not act alone but back any United
Nations initiative.
The Community also called for the immediate dispatch of international
observers to the Serbian-controlled province of Kosovo and neighbouring
countries, to prevent an escalation of the conflict.
Under pressure from Greece, EC leaders said they were ready to recognise
Macedonia's independence provided it chose a name which did not include the
term Macedonia.
</TEXT>
