<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Russia's reformers must disguise their success
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EDWARD BALLS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE INTERNATIONAL Monetary Fund is at present trying to draw up an economic
agreement with the Russian government on the basis of, at best, crude and
partial economic information. But the scale of Russia's task means that even
the statistics that do exist are tricky to interpret. The Russian economy is
shrinking and unemployment is rising.  But does this prove that the reforms
are failing, as opponents argue?  Or, conversely, that a rapid economic
transformation is under way?
Confusion over measures of success and failure have dogged every
reform-minded east European government. Even more than in the west, Russian
policy-makers and headline writers have been educated to believe that rising
production is good and unemployment is bad. Reports that industrial output
fell by 13.2 per cent in the first five months of 1992, compared to the same
period a year ago, or that unemployment has risen by 140 per cent since last
December, must bring beads of sweat to Mr Boris Yeltsin's brow.
Unemployment in Russia is, in fact, very low by western standards.  The
government reports 151,000 registered unemployed in April, just 0.2 per cent
of its 75m workforce, although many of these employees are at present on
semi-permanent paid holidays. Once credits to enterprises dry up, and some
go bankrupt, this hidden unemployment will emerge. The government has
forecast a sixty-fold increase in unemployment to between 3.5m and 4m by the
end of this year, while the International Labour Organisation, an arm of the
UN, expects 10m-11m. But even if the UN's pessimism proves correct, an
unemployment rate of 14.5 per cent would not be much higher than in many
western European countries and lower than in both Spain and Ireland.
A western-style unemployment rate in Russia is necessary to control the
pressure for inflationary wage increases, argues Professor Richard Layard,
of the London School of Economics, and currently an adviser to the Russian
ministry of labour. 'Responsible monetary policy works by creating enough
unemployment to control inflation. . . substantial unemployment is in fact
an inevitable price that is paid for freedom and prosperity.'
Yet while the unemployment side-effect of tight monetary policy in Poland
has proved similar to that of Germany in 1948 or Spain in the late 1970s -
Polish unemployment had to rise further because it started lower, as the
chart shows - its output response has been very different. Output per worker
rose in both Germany and Spain from the beginning of their stabilisation
programmes, although Germany had experienced falls in output in the years
before 1948. But rising unemployment in eastern Europe has been accompanied
by sharp falls in output.
Yet Russia, unlike Spain in the late 1970s, does not need rapidly rising
industrial output. Indeed, it needs the opposite:  de-industrialisation and
the transformation of much of what remains.  Many Russian enterprises are
unviable not because their wage bills are too high but because the market
for their products has disappeared, particularly in the defence industry or
where they relied on intra-eastern European trade. Falling industrial
output, far from being a sign of failure or a necessary evil, will allow the
puny service and retail sectors to expand. Rising unemployment, far from
being a necessary evil, will encourage workers to change jobs.
The Russian government has to ensure that economic upheaval occurs at a
politically acceptable pace. 'As a matter of political economy,' argues
Professor Stanley Fischer of MIT, in a forthcoming Brookings Institute
paper, 'a very rapid decline in production, even production that has
ultimately to disappear, may stop a reform programme in its tracks.' The
Russian government is disguising the true level of unemployment by paying
subsidies to unviable enterprises. The success of its stabilisation
programme will depend on whether it can continue to so until privatisation
nurtures alternative opportunities but without financing its budget deficit
by printing money. Enter the IMF.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT922-288</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CF2APAB7FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920629
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Major satisfied UK has room for manoeuvre
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THERE were no great triumphs for Mr John Major at Lisbon. But then neither
was there the uncomfortable isolation to which Britain has become so
accustomed at European Community summits. So, as he prepares later this week
to take over the EC presidency, Mr Major had few complaints about the
overall outcome.
He lost some battles, notably over the pace of future negotiations on
enlargement, but returned to London content that the tone of the final
communique left plenty of room for Britain to set the agenda over the next
six months.
From his perspective, the summit confirmed that the certainties which had
led many of his colleagues into the Maastricht accord had been replaced by a
more appropriate humility about federalist blueprints following the Danish
people's rejection of the treaty earlier this month.
President Francois Mitterrand - so often scornful of his British
counterparts - added his voice to a barrage of promises from the leaders to
make the Community less remote from its citizens.
Subsidiarity - the principle that power should be devolved to the lowest
possible level - has yet to catch the imagination of Britain's partners. But
Mr Major's colleagues no longer raise their eyes to the heavens when he
argues that the British presidency should place it at the centre of EC
decision-making.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl - repaying the efforts that Mr Major has made to
establish a Bonn-London axis within the Community - proved a stalwart ally.
When German journalists quizzed the chancellor in private over the direction
of the British presidency, he told them not to under-estimate Mr Major's
tenacity and negotiating skills.
Mr Major has no cause for complacency. If he could claim with some justice
that the Community is now ready to debate its future on the basis of his
agenda - above all on decentralisation and the principle of enlargement -
there was much evidence also that his partners believe the European train
has come to only a temporary halt.
For all the compliments offered to his British counterpart, Mr Kohl made it
clear that Bonn will not abandon its ambition to lock Germany into a federal
Europe.
This precarious balance between the pragmatism forced on the Community by
Denmark and federalist ambitions will remain at the heart of the debate over
Europe's future during the presidency, Mr Major's advisers acknowledge.
By the Edinburgh summit in December, Mr Major will have to give substance to
the notion of subsidiarity.
It will not be easy. While Britain sees it as the instrument to tame
Brussels, Mr Jacques Delors has a rather different concept.
The Commission president is happy to devolve back to national governments
much of the policing of Community law. But he - and many of Mr Major's
European counterparts - do not see that as a brake on greater authority at
the centre for decisions on economic, foreign and security policies.
The debate, though, is on ground chosen for once by Britain.
Mr Major is confident that by the Edinburgh summit there will be a stronger
recognition that his agenda matches the mood of Europe. But, as Mrs Margaret
Thatcher reminded him yesterday, he has first to demonstrate that he can
deliver on his promises.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
</PAGE>
</DOC>
