<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Mitterrand praised for daring visit to Sarajevo: Shelling
erupts after French president seeks to bring hope to embattled Bosnians
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, SARAJEVO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FRENCH president Francois Mitterrand flew out of the besieged Bosnian
capital of Sarajevo yesterday evening after a daring visit by helicopter to
the city's 300,000 starving inhabitants.
The dramatic six-hour stopover ended with the 75-year-old head of state in a
flak jacket, taking shelter in a building near Sarajevo airport after Serb
tanks and heavy machine guns on the runway renewed their assault on the
suburb of Dobrinja. As the president's helicopter took off, Serb irregulars
and Serbia's proxy Bosnian army based at the airport began shelling
Dobrinja, under siege for more than 50 days.
Mr Mitterrand said a second helicopter carrying aides and French security
men was hit during the skirmish, in which Moslem snipers wounded five
Serbian fighters.
Last night Tanjug, the Belgrade-based news agency, reported that the
Bosnian-Serb leaders had handed over control of the airport to United
Nations peacekeeping forces. This could pave the way for humanitarian aid
but Gen Lewis MacKenzie, UN commander in Sarajevo, said his troops could
still not claim full responsibility for the airport because the Serbs were
still there.
President Mitterrand finally flew out of the airport in his helicopter at
14.40 GMT to Split, where his Falcon 900 jet took him to Paris. One of its
wings was taped up after being damaged by a police vehicle at Sarajevo's
Butmir airfield.
His visit to what was once one of the finest cities in the Balkans started
soon after the European Community heads of state summit ended in Lisbon, the
Portuguese capital, on Saturday.
His EC colleagues were apparently kept in the dark about his intentions. But
Mr Mitterrand told Portuguese president Mario Soares and German chancellor
Helmut Kohl about his plans by telephone before leaving.
Mr Douglas Hurd, UK foreign secretary, said: 'It's a brave act by an elderly
president . . . I take my hat off to him.'
In Paris, Mr Nicolas Sarkozy, deputy secretary-general of the conservative
Rally for the Republic, the main opposition party, saluted the panache of Mr
Mitterrand's 'beau geste'.
French officials said the president had wanted to fly on Saturday directly
to Sarajevo, whose airport has been blockaded by Serb forces for nearly
three months, but it was too dangerous. The airport has no lights, and the
runway was strewn with military equipment and shells left from weeks of
heavy fighting.
Instead, on Saturday night, Mr Mitterrand flew to the Croatian city of
Split, on the Adriatic coast. Officials there advised him against travelling
to Sarajevo.
Undaunted, the president, apparently deeply affected by an impassioned plea
of help and support last week by Bosnian president Alija Izetbegovic,
refused to abandon his mission.
'I hope to contribute to the opening of Sarajevo to the outside world,' Mr
Mitterrand said as he left Split for Sarajevo.
'I want to see, witness, observe and hear.'
Two Transall transport aircraft of the French air force, each carrying 6.5
tonnes of food and medicine, set off for Sarajevo immediately after Mr
Mitterrand's visit. But last night they were unable to proceed beyond Split.
Mr Mitterrand's mission began as the white presidential helicopter touched
down at Butmir airfield, about 15km south of the city centre.
Armed UN peacekeeping troops fanned out across the runway as the president
emerged from the aircraft. He was bundled into a UN armoured vehicle and
driven at high speed through the centre of Sarajevo to UN headquarters.
Undaunted by snipers, Mr Mitterrand made an impromptu walk through the city
with Mr Izetbegovic. Both presidents laid a red rose on a makeshift altar at
the central street where at least 16 people were killed in a Serb mortar
attack last month.
Mr Mitterrand held talks in the pock-marked presidency building with Mr
Izetbegovic and Mr Stjepan Klujic, a senior Croat member of the Bosnian
government.
Mr Radovan Karadzic, head of the Bosnian Serbs, and a close ally of Serbian
president Slobodan Milosevic, flew in from Pale, his headquarters east of
Sarajevo, to talk to Mr Mitterrand.
