<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Economics: Markets on tenterhooks over Fed's next move
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTORS and financial markets will be on tenterhooks this week in case the
US Federal Reserve decides on a further easing of monetary policy.
The Federal Open Market Committee, the Fed's top decision-making body, meets
tomorrow amid fears that the US economic recovery may fade. Several
important US indicators are scheduled during the week, beginning with
consumer confidence tomorrow, the national purchasing managers' report on
Wednesday and ending with labour market data on Thursday. Some analysts have
suggested that poor labour market figures could prompt the Fed to cut rates
after discussion of such a move in the FOMC.
Highlights of the week ahead, with the median of forecasts from MMS
International, the financial information company, in brackets include:
Today: Luxembourg, EC finance ministers meet to discuss directives on
minimum indirect taxes and investment services. US, May home sales
(550,000), June farm prices. UK, final May money supply figures. France, May
final consumer prices. Canada, March wages and salaries.
Tomorrow: US, Federal Open Market Committee meets, May leading indicators
(up 0.6 per cent), June consumer confidence (73 per cent), June Chicago
purchasing managers' report. UK, first quarter real personal disposable
income (up 0.2 per cent), first quarter savings ratio (10.2 per cent).
France, May unemployment (10 per cent). Japan, May housing starts (up 3 per
cent on year), construction orders, construction starts, unemployment.
Canada, April real GDP at factor cost (up 0.3 per cent), building permits
(up 1 per cent).
Wednesday: UK takes over EC presidency. Germany, Finance Minister Theo
Waigel presents 1993 Federal Budget. US, June NAPM (56.3 per cent), May
construction spending (up 0.5 per cent). Japan, June foreign exchange
reserves. Australia, May building approvals (down 1 per cent), current
account (seasonally adjusted ADollars 1.1bn deficit).
Thursday: Germany, regular Bundesbank council meeting. US, June non-farm
payrolls (up 95,000), manufacturing payrolls (up 10,500), civilian
unemployment (7.4 per cent), average work week, hourly earnings, Michigan
sentiment index; May factory orders, shipments; initial claims for week to
June 20; money supply for week to June 22, release of May 19 FOMC minutes.
UK, June official reserves (up Dollars 50m).
Friday: US, all markets close for Independence Day holiday. UK, May housing
starts and completions, first quarter house renovations. Canada, June
foreign reserves.
Saturday: UK, Japan-EC discussions in London.
During the week: Germany, June preliminary cost of living (up 0.3 per cent
on month, 4.3 per cent on year), May import prices (up 0.2 per cent on
month, down 2.1 per cent on year), industrial production (down 0.2 per
cent), manufacturing output (down 0.2 per cent), manufacturing orders (up
0.2 per cent), May trade balance, current account. Switzerland, June Zurich
CPI. Japan, May foreign bond investment, trade balance, current account on
IMF basis.
</TEXT>
