<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / International Company News: US financings set records
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
US COMPANIES raised a record Dollars 420bn in new equity and debt issues
during the first half of this year, according to preliminary figures
released by Securities Data, the US financial information specialist. In the
first half of 1991, Dollars 280bn was raised in new issues,
Two factors were behind the record financings: historically low US interest
rates, and buoyant stock markets. The lowest interest rates in almost 30
years fuelled a boom in the corporate bonds market, with companies raising
Dollars 146bn in 929 issues of new debt, 43 per cent more than in the first
half of 1991.
Even the much-derided junk bond market enjoyed a banner first half.
Offerings of high-yield corporate bonds reached a record Dollars 18.8bn,
beating the Dollars 16.7bn raised in the second half of 1986.
In the equity markets, the continued strength in prices resulted in a record
603 issues worth Dollars 41.3bn being sold to investors, topping the
previous year's first-half record of Dollars 27bn. Initial public offerings
(IPOs) of stock also set a record at Dollars 19.6bn.
</TEXT>
