FT  29 JUN 92 / Prescott will argue case for BR leasing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN PRESCOTT, shadow transport secretary, will argue in a speech
tomorrow that freeing British Rail to enter unhindered into lease agreements
with private companies would cut the real cost of buying new rolling stock.
Mr Prescott, a candidate for the Labour deputy leadership, will refine his
calls for the rules governing BR's access to private finance to be made less
restrictive and condemn the government's 'ideologically prejudiced' attitude
to the funding of public bodies.
Speaking in Llandudno, north Wales, within weeks of BR's expected
announcement of an annual loss of Pounds 150m, he will urge the government
to accept that the organisation is in financial crisis.
Focusing on the planned Pounds 860m upgrading of the west coast main line
from Euston to Glasgow, Mr Prescott will explain that a leasing deal would
cut costs if the lender could be persuaded to pass on a portion of the tax
benefits accruing from the transaction.
He will advocate that the estimated Pounds 530m cost of new trains for the
line and a new West Midlands maintenance depot be financed by leasing. The
Pounds 330m cost of infrastructure improvements should be generated by
permitting BR to raise an index-linked bond.
Present accounting conventions remove the advantages of such techniques as
leasing for public bodies such as BR.
