<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Call for standard post-16 training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VOCATIONAL education and training for people aged 16 to 18 should be
tailored to a uniform standard, the National Commission on Education urges
today.
The commission, a privately funded body, said that a unified system would
improve the quality of the workforce. In a discussion paper, it calls for a
common core curriculum of mathematics, science, technology, English and
another European language, whether in full-time education, on Youth Training
or in traineeships run by employers.
Establishing a high-quality, broadly based education at all ages and levels
is essential if the UK is to develop a flexible and committed workforce, the
paper argues.
The government, employers, unions and educational institutions should all be
brought together, the paper says.
But it warns that it will be vital to determine which of those
'stakeholders' would carry primary responsibility.
Local enterprise companies, the organisations created by the government to
improve Scotland's training and environment, are suffering because they have
too little discretion and are struggling to adapt existing working practices
of staff, according to a report.
Academics from the London School of Economics argue that many of the
difficulties arise from Treasury and Department of Employment funding
constraints south of the border.
The report questions whether staff seconded from the Civil Service 'possess
the required expertise and competence' for the job.
Towards a well qualified workforce. National Commission on Education, Suite
24, 10 Manor Gardens, London N7 6JY. Free.
Scotland's LECs. London School of Economics, Houghton Street, London, WC2A
2AE. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
