<HEADLINE>
FT  29 JUN 92 / Mitterrand in Sarajevo: War of terror against Trans Dnestr
dissidents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRYSTIA FREELAND
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOLDOVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE bullet-ridden buildings and bloody streets of Bendery in the separatist
Trans Dnestr region of Moldova testify to the violence that claimed 300
lives there last weekend. But terrified locals amid the fertile fields and
whitewashed cottages north west of the strategic border town speak of a
quiet war of terror which is exacting a less visible toll.
On the eve of a United Nations fact-finding mission to Trans Dnestr, local
people have recounted tales of Trans Dnestr forces killing political
opponents or intimidating them into silence or exile.
Victims say the violence is orchestrated by the leadership of the Trans
Dnestr region with the co-operation of hardline forces in Moscow. Moldova
wants to unite with Romania; Trans Dnestr is dominated by ethnic Russians
and Ukrainians who are fighting this move and are backed by hardliners in
Moscow.
Members of the Trans Dnestr military forces have admitted that they have
acted to 'silence' and 'isolate' local dissenters. The Trans Dnestr
government acknowledges the existence of rogue elements in the breakaway
region's many military groups but has denied complicity in an orchestrated
campaign of intimidation.
'We isolated those who spoke openly against us,' said Mr Misha Russkiy, an
ethnic Russian tractor driver, who now serves in the newly-formed militia of
the Grigoriopol region, an enclave of ethnic Moldovans in Trans Dnestr.
'As long as they do not speak out openly no one touches them,' Mr Russkiy
said, surrounded by a group of comrades casually clutching their
Kalashnikovs.
An ethnic Moldovan community leader from the area, who last year spoke out
for a united Moldova, described how that silence has been secured. Last
January he began to receive nocturnal visits from members of the Trans
Dnestr Republican Guard, who demanded at gunpoint that he should leave the
region.
One morning in the middle of March a dozen Republican Guards stormed his
office and took him to a basement cell, where his kidneys were beaten with
the butt of a Kalashnikov, and his jaw, which is still swollen, was struck
by a 2lb machine-gun magazine.
He believes he survived only because his loyal employees took to the town's
central square demanding his release. With their support he has managed to
stay on in the terrorised region.
By contrast Mr Anatoly Danilov, a slim, blue-eyed, ethnic-Russian newspaper
editor from the town of Grigoriopol, was forced to flee because he supported
a united Moldova. After months of menacing telephone calls and an evening
visit and beating administered by seven Republican Guards, Mr Danilov said
that on March 13 he was warned by telephone that he was on a list of people
to be 'neutralised' and must leave immediately.
He did, and from the safety of Kishinev he spoke of 15-20 other locals who
have disappeared, including one, Mr Anatoly Dikusar, whose body, when
discovered in a field on April 20, 'looked like it had been through a meat
grinder'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
