FT  27 JUN 92 / International Company News: Reichmanns ordered to reveal
more details of wealth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A TORONTO judge has ordered the Reichmann family to disclose more details
about their private wealth in response to creditors' concern that the family
should contribute towards the costs of running and restructuring their
ailing company, Olympia &amp; York.
The order affects companies which the creditors believe may in some way be
related to the O&amp;Y group but which fall outside the scope of the court
protection order granted last month. The order, issued under Canada's
Companies Creditors Arrangements Act, affects 29 companies under the main
holding group, Olympia &amp; York Developments.
The Reichmanns are expected to contest the order in court on Monday. For the
first time since the bankruptcy filing last month, they will be represented,
not by O&amp;Y's law firm, Davies Ward Beck of Toronto, but by a personal
lawyer.
The creditors have succeeded in recent weeks in drawing considerably more
information out of the Reichmanns than was disclosed in the original CCAA
filing.
Mr Gary Goodman, a senior O&amp;Y official, disclosed under private
cross-examination last week that the family has bought assets worth several
hundred million dollars from O&amp;Y over the past 18 months. An O&amp;Y spokesman
said this was done to inject cash into the company as it became more pressed
for liquidity.
Earlier this week, O&amp;Y disclosed other unencumbered assets worth about
CDollars 70m (USDollars 58.3m), including a Gulfstream jet and several
parcels of land.
A lawyer for one of the creditors said yesterday: 'We want disclosure. If
they have a house, I'd like to know they have a house. Once we get the
information, we can make a decision on what to do.'
Creditors with loans secured by O&amp;Y projects want to reduce their
contribution to the company's administrative and restructuring expenses.
